<h2>The Three Stages</h2>

<p>The Eastern Fathers describe three stages in the life of the Jesus Prayer:</p>

<p><strong>Oral prayer.</strong> The prayer is on the lips. It requires effort, attention, deliberate repetition. The mind wanders constantly. This stage can last months or years — and that is perfectly normal.</p>

<p><strong>Mental prayer.</strong> The prayer moves from the lips to the mind. You begin to think the prayer rather than say it. Distractions decrease (though they never vanish entirely). The prayer begins to feel more natural, less forced.</p>

<p><strong>Prayer of the heart.</strong> The prayer "descends into the heart" — the deepest center of the person. It becomes continuous, running as a quiet undercurrent beneath all other activity. The Fathers describe this stage as a kind of joyful awareness of God's presence that persists even during conversation, work, and sleep.</p>

<p>Most people spend their entire lives in the first or second stage. That is not failure. It is faithfulness. The Jesus Prayer is not a technique for producing spiritual experiences. It is a relationship with a Person — and relationships develop at their own pace.</p>

<p>Start today. Say the words. Come back tomorrow and say them again. That is all the technique you need.</p>

